15
01:24:00,000 --> 01:30:00,000
They picture a training job running for six hours,
getting interrupted at hour five, losing everything, and starting over.

16
01:30:00,000 --> 01:36:00,000
They picture angry data scientists.
They picture missed deadlines.

17
01:36:00,000 --> 01:42:00,000
They picture the chaos of a production incident
caused by AWS reclaiming an instance.

18
01:42:00,000 --> 01:48:00,000
So they run everything On-Demand.
They pay full price. They feel safe.

19
01:48:00,000 --> 01:54:00,000
What they are actually paying for is the illusion of safety.
Because On-Demand instances can also be terminated.
AWS reboots for maintenance.

20
01:54:00,000 --> 02:00:00,000
And the cost is real.
For a startup running eight GPU training jobs per night
at one dollar twenty cents per hour for four hours each.

21
02:00:00,000 --> 02:06:00,000
That is one thousand one hundred fifty-two dollars per month
on compute that runs while most of the company sleeps.

22
02:06:00,000 --> 02:12:00,000
With Spot engineering done correctly,
that same workload costs two hundred eighty-eight to
three hundred forty-five dollars per month. Seventy to seventy-five percent cheaper.

23
02:12:00,000 --> 02:18:00,000
Zero lost jobs. Zero failed training runs.

24
02:18:00,000 --> 02:24:00,000
The difference is not luck. It is engineering.

25
02:24:00,000 --> 02:30:00,000
Let me explain how Spot interruptions actually work.
Understanding the mechanism removes the fear.

26
02:30:00,000 --> 02:36:00,000
When AWS needs capacity back, the sequence is.

27
02:36:00,000 --> 02:42:00,000
Step one. AWS decides to reclaim your Spot instance.

28
02:42:00,000 --> 02:48:00,000
Step two. AWS publishes an interruption notice to the
EC2 Instance Metadata Service. IMDS for short.

29
02:48:00,000 --> 02:54:00,000
The endpoint is http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/spot/termination-time.

30
02:54:00,000 --> 03:00:00,000
Step three. The endpoint returns a UTC timestamp.
The exact time the instance will be terminated.

31
03:00:00,000 --> 03:06:00,000
Step four. You have approximately two minutes between when the notice appears
and when the instance is killed.

32
03:06:00,000 --> 03:12:00,000
Step five. AWS also publishes an EventBridge event
and an SQS message so Karpenter can act at the cluster level.

33
03:12:00,000 --> 03:18:00,000
Two minutes is enough time to.
Save a model checkpoint to S3. Flush in-flight data to PostgreSQL.

34
03:18:00,000 --> 03:24:00,000
Complete the current batch and mark it done.
Signal the orchestration layer to reschedule on a new instance.

35
03:24:00,000 --> 03:30:00,000
Two minutes is not enough time to.
Train a new epoch. Run inference on a large batch.

36
03:30:00,000 --> 03:36:00,000
Do anything you have not already designed for.

37
03:36:00,000 --> 03:42:00,000
The engineering question is not how do I avoid interruptions.
It is how do I make interruptions cost me less than two minutes of work.

