44
04:18:00,000 --> 04:24:00,000
First, let's analyse Spot price stability.
Before picking instance types, understand their price stability.

45
04:24:00,000 --> 04:30:00,000
A Spot instance family with volatile prices will interrupt you frequently.
One with stable prices might run for weeks uninterrupted.

46
04:30:00,000 --> 04:36:00,000
Create a script called spot-stability-analysis.sh.

47
04:36:00,000 --> 04:42:00,000
Define your candidate instance types.
g4dn.xlarge, g4dn.2xlarge, g5.xlarge, g5.2xlarge, p3.2xlarge.

48
04:42:00,000 --> 04:48:00,000
Look back seven days.
For each instance type, get the Spot price history.

49
04:48:00,000 --> 04:54:00,000
Use Python to calculate statistics.
Average price, minimum, maximum, current price.

50
04:54:00,000 --> 05:00:00,000
Calculate the coefficient of variation.
Standard deviation divided by average, times one hundred.

51
05:00:00,000 --> 05:06:00,000
The coefficient of variation tells you how stable the price is.
Lower is more stable.

52
05:06:00,000 --> 05:12:00,000
If the coefficient of variation is less than five percent,
the interruption risk is low. Excellent Spot candidate. Use freely.

53
05:12:00,000 --> 05:18:00,000
If it is between five and fifteen percent,
the interruption risk is medium. Good candidate. Checkpoint every five minutes.

54
05:18:00,000 --> 05:24:00,000
If it is greater than fifteen percent,
the interruption risk is high. Use with On-Demand fallback only.

55
05:24:00,000 --> 05:30:00,000
Run the script.
You will see the stability scores for each instance type.

56
05:30:00,000 --> 05:36:00,000
A real finding from riskoracle.
g4dn.xlarge in us-east-1 runs at a coefficient of variation less than three percent.

57
05:36:00,000 --> 05:42:00,000
It almost never gets interrupted.
p3.2xlarge runs at about eighteen percent. Much more volatile.

58
05:42:00,000 --> 05:48:00,000
We run training jobs on g4dn with Spot.
We only fall back to p3 on-demand for the final evaluation run
that cannot be interrupted.

